n temporary agricultural jobs from 1942 to 1964—forged domesticity and intimacy, sharing affection but also physical violence. Through these case studies that reexamine the diasporic male private sphere, Guidotti-Hernández formulates a theory of transnational Mexican masculinities rooted in emotional and physical intimacy that emerged from the experiences of being racial, political, and social outsiders in the United States.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aEmigration and immigrationxPsychological aspects. 0aMasculinityzMexican-American Border Region. 0aMasculinityzMexico. 0aMenxSocializationzMexico. 0aMenzMexicoxIdentity. 0aSex discrimination against womenxPolitical aspectszMexico. 7aHISTORY / Latin America / Mexico.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDuke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311074331940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781478021469zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781478021469423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781478021469/original  a978-3-11-074331-9  Duke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles